Besides, the Italians have tried, over and over again, to vary the form of their verses; some have wished to measure them by musical rhythm others have contented themselves with making blank verse. They have neither succeeded completely nor failed completely. Their language sweet and musical lacks force whether in good or in evil. Its words might indeed, strictly speaking, be composed of long and short syllables; but as they terminate, nearly all, in the soit and languid style that we call feminine, it results, therefore, that in the measured verses the poets laclr the long syllables to constitute the last ioot and to form the spondee, and that in the blank verse they are obliged to terminate thern all in the same style: so that with the meas· ure they create only lame verses, and without the rhyme they make them all equally languid.¹
